<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="27" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="27">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hedqvist" authorityYear="1967" class="Insecta" family="Proteaceae" genus="Dinapsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dinapsis albicoxa" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albicoxa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Dinapsis albicoxa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is currently only known from a few localities in southeast Madagascar. The holotype locality (Mandraka) is situated east of Manjakandriana (Antananarivo Province) There is a tiny settlement (-18.905361, 47.920253) 10 km east of Manjakandriana near the Mandraka Catholic church. The Mandraka River runs through this region and there is a Mandraka waterfall in the area. Seyrig may have been referring to the river/waterfall area rather than the precise settlement. Ivondro is located in the Atsimo-Atsinanana region.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="27">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hedqvist" authorityYear="1967" class="Insecta" family="Proteaceae" genus="Dinapsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dinapsis albicoxa" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albicoxa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Dinapsis albicoxa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a distinctive species that is named for its white hind coxa (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Dinapsis albicoxa female (Ranomafana National Park, 21 ˚ 14 ' 18.48 &quot; S, 47 ˚ 23 ' 40.50 &quot; E, alt. 1138 m, Madagascar). Photograph copyright Steve Marshall (used with permission)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1112.82307.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/714017" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">1</figureCitation>
). The hind coxa is entirely white in the holotype, as well as the specimen examined from Fianarantsoa; however, the specimen from Ivondro has some brown colour basally and is not entirely white. To avoid confusion with any other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Waterston" authorityYear="1922" class="Insecta" family="Proteaceae" genus="Dinapsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dinapsis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Dinapsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species that may have white colour on the hind coxa apically, it is important to examine the characteristics of the mesoscutum laterally. Specimens of 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. albicoxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" rank="species" species="albicoxa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">D. albicoxa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have the mesoscutum with a strongly projecting lobe-like carina situated posterolaterally (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Dinapsis albicoxa holotype female (MNHN). Note: at some point this specimen was broken and repaired incorrectly, with the face glued to the mesosoma A habitus, dorsal view B habitus, lateral view C head (lateral view), mesosoma, dorsal view D head, dorsal view, mesosoma lateral view E head, posterior view F wings. Scale bars: 1000 µm (A, D, F); 2000 µm (B); 500 µm (C, E)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1112.82307.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/714019" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">3C</figureCitation>
) and darkly banded wings (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Dinapsis albicoxa holotype female (MNHN). Note: at some point this specimen was broken and repaired incorrectly, with the face glued to the mesosoma A habitus, dorsal view B habitus, lateral view C head (lateral view), mesosoma, dorsal view D head, dorsal view, mesosoma lateral view E head, posterior view F wings. Scale bars: 1000 µm (A, D, F); 2000 µm (B); 500 µm (C, E)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1112.82307.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/714019" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">3F</figureCitation>
). It should be noted that while the entirely white hind coxa is a useful diagnostic feature for 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. albicoxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" rank="species" species="albicoxa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">D. albicoxa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, there are several unrelated, undescribed species in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hedqvist" authorityYear="1967" class="Insecta" family="Proteaceae" genus="Dinapsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dinapsis oculohirta" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oculohirta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Dinapsis oculohirta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group that also have the hind coxa mostly white.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
